instructions:
## Set up a Hono API server

### 1. Install packages

**For Node.js:**
```bash
npm install hono @hono/node-server
npm install -D tsx typescript @types/node
```

**For Bun (no adapter needed):**
```bash
bun add hono
```

- `hono` — the core framework (works on every JS runtime)
- `@hono/node-server` — Node.js-specific adapter; not needed for Bun, Deno, or Cloudflare Workers
- `tsx` — for running TypeScript directly during development (Node.js only)
- Do NOT install `express` or `fastify` — Hono replaces them

### 2. Create the Hono app (`src/app.ts`)
```ts
import { Hono } from 'hono';
import { cors } from 'hono/cors';
import { logger } from 'hono/logger';
import { prettyJSON } from 'hono/pretty-json';

const app = new Hono();

app.use('*', cors());
app.use('*', logger());
app.use('*', prettyJSON());

app.get('/health', (c) => c.json({ status: 'ok' }));

export default app;
```
- `cors()`, `logger()`, and `prettyJSON()` are built-in Hono middleware — no extra packages needed.
- `app.use('*', ...)` applies middleware to ALL routes. Apply middleware before route definitions.

### 3. Start the server

**`src/index.ts` for Node.js:**
```ts
import { serve } from '@hono/node-server';
import app from './app';

const port = Number(process.env.PORT) || 3000;
console.log(`Listening on http://localhost:${port}`);
serve({ fetch: app.fetch, port });
```

**`src/index.ts` for Bun:**
```ts
import app from './app';

export default {
  port: Number(process.env.PORT) || 3000,
  fetch: app.fetch,
};
```

Add scripts to `package.json`:
```json
"scripts": {
  "dev": "tsx watch src/index.ts",
  "build": "tsc",
  "start": "node dist/index.js"
}
```

### 4. Zod input validation
Install the validator middleware:
```bash
npm install @hono/zod-validator zod
```

Create a route with validated input (`src/routes/posts.ts`):
```ts
import { Hono } from 'hono';
import { zValidator } from '@hono/zod-validator';
import { z } from 'zod';

const posts = new Hono();

const createPostSchema = z.object({
  title: z.string().min(1),
  body: z.string(),
});

posts.get('/', (c) => c.json({ posts: [] }));

posts.post(
  '/',
  zValidator('json', createPostSchema),
  async (c) => {
    const data = c.req.valid('json'); // typed as { title: string; body: string }
    return c.json({ id: crypto.randomUUID(), ...data }, 201);
  }
);

posts.get('/:id', (c) => {
  const id = c.req.param('id');
  return c.json({ id, title: 'Example' });
});

export { posts };
```
- `c.req.valid('json')` returns a fully-typed object inferred from the Zod schema.
- The 201 second argument sets the HTTP status code.

### 5. Compose sub-routers
```ts
// src/app.ts
import { Hono } from 'hono';
import { posts } from './routes/posts';
import { users } from './routes/users';

const app = new Hono();

app.use('*', cors());
app.use('*', logger());

app.route('/api/posts', posts);
app.route('/api/users', users);

app.get('/health', (c) => c.json({ status: 'ok' }));

export default app;
```
- Each sub-router is a separate `new Hono()` instance mounted with `app.route()`.
- Middleware defined on the root app applies to all sub-routers.

### 6. Custom auth middleware
```ts
import { createMiddleware } from 'hono/factory';
import { HTTPException } from 'hono/http-exception';

type Variables = { userId: string };

export const authMiddleware = createMiddleware<{ Variables: Variables }>(async (c, next) => {
  const token = c.req.header('Authorization')?.replace('Bearer ', '');
  if (!token) throw new HTTPException(401, { message: 'Unauthorized' });

  // Verify JWT — replace with your preferred library (jose, jsonwebtoken, etc.)
  const userId = verifyJwt(token); // returns userId string or throws
  c.set('userId', userId);
  await next();
});
```

Apply to a route group:
```ts
const api = new Hono<{ Variables: Variables }>();
api.use('*', authMiddleware);
api.get('/me', (c) => {
  const userId = c.get('userId'); // fully typed — no cast needed
  return c.json({ userId });
});
```
- `HTTPException` sends the correct status code and JSON error body automatically.
- The `Variables` generic makes `c.get()` / `c.set()` type-safe.

### 7. TypeScript config (`tsconfig.json`)
```json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "target": "ES2022",
    "module": "NodeNext",
    "moduleResolution": "NodeNext",
    "outDir": "dist",
    "rootDir": "src",
    "strict": true
  },
  "include": ["src"]
}
```

### 8. Verify the API
```bash
# Start dev server
npm run dev

# Health check
curl http://localhost:3000/health
# Expected: {"status":"ok"}

# Create a post
curl -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/posts \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  -d '{"title": "Hello", "body": "World"}'
# Expected: 201 {"id":"...","title":"Hello","body":"World"}

# Validation error
curl -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/posts \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  -d '{"title": ""}'
# Expected: 400 with Zod error details
```

### Common errors & fixes
- **`Cannot find module '@hono/node-server'`** → Not installed. Run `npm install @hono/node-server`. Skip for Bun.
- **`TypeError: fetch is not a function`** → Node.js version is below 18 which lacks global `fetch`. Upgrade to Node.js 18+.
- **`zValidator is not a function`** → `@hono/zod-validator` not installed. Run `npm install @hono/zod-validator`.
- **`c.req.valid('json')` returns `unknown`** → The validator middleware is not chained before the handler in the same `.post()` call. The validator must be the argument immediately before the handler.
- **CORS errors in browser** → `cors()` middleware is applied after route definitions, or not applied at all. Move `app.use('*', cors())` to the top of `app.ts`.
- **404 on all routes** → Sub-router mounted with a path that doesn't match. Check `app.route()` paths vs. the fetch URL.
- **Port already in use** → Kill the existing process or set `PORT=3001` in your shell.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT install `@hono/node-server` when targeting Bun or Cloudflare Workers — use the runtime's native entry point instead.
- Do NOT use Express-style middleware (`body-parser`, `helmet`, etc.) — they are incompatible with Hono's fetch-based API.
- Do NOT read `await c.req.json()` after `c.req.valid('json')` — the body stream can only be consumed once. Use `c.req.valid('json')` when a validator is present.
- Do NOT skip `@hono/zod-validator` and validate manually — the validator integrates with TypeScript inference and sets proper 400 responses automatically.
- Do NOT put all routes in one file — split by resource into `src/routes/*.ts` files and compose with `app.route()`.
- Do NOT hardcode the port — always read from `process.env.PORT` for production deployments.
